s":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cusack","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aileen, Brigid, Eamon, Fergus, Seamus.","Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Cussac in Guienne, France, named with the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Cūcius</i> or <i>Cussius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. The surname died out in England, but is common in Ireland, where it was imported at the time of the Anglo-Norman invasion in the 12th century. It has been Gaelicized as <b>de Cíosóg</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Cuzick","meanings":["Irish and English (Worcestershire): variant of   Cusack  . This form of the surname is no longer found in Ireland and is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Cusick","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: variant of   Cusack  , now found predominantly in Scotland.","Americanized form of Polish   Kusik   or Czech <b>Kusík</b>, Slovak <b>Kúšik</b> and <b>Kušík</b>.","Americanized form of Croatian <b>Kusić</b>, Croatian and Serbian <b>Kušić</b> (see   Kusic  ), or Serbian <b>Ćušić</b> (see   Cusic  )."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margery de Cusack was born about 1277, in Killeen, County Meath, Ireland, her father, Adam Cusack II, 3rd Lord of Killeen, was 37 and her mother, Alicia, was 37.